  abstract = {Halo occupation distribution (HOD) models describe the number of galaxies that reside in different haloes, and are widely used in galaxy-halo connection studies using the halo model (HM). Here, we introduce and study HOD response functions \$R\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$ that describe the response of the HODs to long-wavelength perturbations \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}\$. The linear galaxy bias parameters \$b\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$ are a weighted version of \$b\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}h + R\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$, where \$b\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}h\$ is the halo bias, but the contribution from \$R\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$ is routinely ignored in the literature. We investigate the impact of this by measuring the \$R\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$ in separate universe simulations of the IllustrisTNG model for three types of perturbations: total matter perturbations, \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}={\textbackslash}delta\_m\$; baryon-CDM compensated isocurvature perturbations, \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}={\textbackslash}sigma\$; and potential perturbations with local primordial non-Gaussianity, \${\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textbackslash}propto f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm NL\}{\textbackslash}phi\$. Our main takeaway message is that the \$R\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$ are not negligible in general and their size should be estimated on a case-by-case basis. For stellar-mass selected galaxies, the responses \$R\_{\textbackslash}phi{\textasciicircum}g\$ and \$R\_{\textbackslash}sigma{\textasciicircum}g\$ are sizeable and cannot be neglected in HM calculations of the bias parameters \$b\_{\textbackslash}phi{\textasciicircum}g\$ and \$b\_{\textbackslash}sigma{\textasciicircum}g\$; this is relevant to constrain inflation using galaxies. On the other hand, we do not detect a strong impact of the HOD response \$R\_1{\textasciicircum}g\$ on the linear galaxy bias \$b\_1{\textasciicircum}g\$. These results can be explained by the impact that the perturbations have on stellar-to-total-mass relations. We also look into the impact on the bias of the gas distribution and find similar conclusions. We show that a single extra parameter describing the overall amplitude of \$R\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$ recovers the measured \$b\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$ well, which indicates that \$R\_{\textbackslash}mathcal\{O\}{\textasciicircum}g\$ can be easily added to HM/HOD studies as a new ingredient.},
  keywords = {Astrophysics - Cosmology and Nongalactic Astrophysics},
